Customizing The TopSpeed Environment - TSCFG
=============================================

The TopSpeed configuration text file (TSCFG.TXT) and other files
TS*.TXT included by it contain the message text, menu
definitions, project system configuration and compiler
definitions installed in the TopSpeed System.

This information may be 're-compiled' (using TSCFG.EXE) to
produce a new TSDATA.OVL data overlay which is read whenever
the TopSpeed environment is entered. This allows you to change
your environment menu layout, hot keys, Editing keys and text
messages to your own requirements.

The top-level configuration file TSCFG.TXT sets some directives
(see below), then includes other .TXT files which contain
configuration text as follows:

  TSMAIN.TXT    editor keys, menus, and environment options
  TSPRJ.TXT     configuration of project system (see Developers
                Guide).
  TSMAKE.TXT    Messages and initialization data for Project
                System and Linker
  TSISL.TXT     Messages for code generator
  TSCPP.TXT     C++ compiler messages
  TSC.TXT       C compiler messages
  TSPAS.TXT     Pascal compiler messages
  TSMOD.TXT     Modula2 compiler messages

To run TSCFG.EXE just type:

   TSCFG

at the main DOS or OS/2 prompt in the system directory where
you keep TSDATA.OVL. This will create a new TSDATA.OVL,
and the old TSDATA.OVL is renamed to TSDATA.OLD. The new
configuration can then be immediately used on starting the
TopSpeed Environment.

You are encouraged to experiment by changing the TopSpeed
Configuration File TSMAIN.TXT to discover the setup that best
suits you. However, before you edit TSMAIN.TXT, you should save
a copy of the file, in case you later want to go back to the
default definitions supplied with the TopSpeed system.

The following sections describe changes you can make within
the Menu Definition File.



Changing the Main Menu Type
---------------------------

You can use three types of menus: pop-up, pull-down, and bar.
The type of the main menu is defined by the line

! LinePull                 | [ TopSpeed ]  <F10> <AltF9> <AltF10>

which defines a "Bar" style menu (i.e. a Pull-Down menu with no
frame). If you wish to have a horizontal "Pull-Down" menu with a
frame, you should change LinePull to PullDown. If you want a
vertical "Pop-Up" style menu, you should change LinePull to
PopUp.

If you wish to change the title displayed at the top of a menu,
you can  edit the "TopSpeed" between the square brackets ('['
and ']'). For example, you may want to change it to:

!PullDown [ My TopSpeed C,  Hands Off! ] | <F10>

You  can  also  change  the key that invokes  the  main  menu
by changing the  <F10> after the '|' . For example, if you need
ShiftF10 to invoke the main menu you might have the line:

!PullDown [ TopSpeed ] | <ShiftF10>


Changing Menu Text
------------------

In the Menu Definition File, you can change the text displayed
in the menu by editing the appropriate line. For example, if you
want to change Files to read PcDos on the Main Menu you can
change the line:

{F}iles   | <AltF>

to

{P}cDos   | <AltF>

Note that the character enclosed in the braces ( { and } )
defines the command character that invokes the menu line.
This command character may be in the middle of the word - for
example, Pc{D}os - or left out altogether if not required.

The number of leading spaces before the menu text defines the
Level of the menu within the menu tree. Don't change this
unless the menu tree is to be changed, as described in the
next section.


Changing the Menu Tree
----------------------

In addition to changing the text of the menu, you can also
change the actual structure of the menu tree. This means you
can reorder menus, create new submenus or even delete
unwanted commands.

To illustrate how to change the menu tree, suppose you wish
to group the "Compilation  Functions" together in a  single
menu. To do this, the lines containing:

{E}dit               | Editor        <AltE>
{C}ompile            | Compiler      <AltC>
{L}ink               | Linker        <AltL>
{M}ake               | Make          <AltM>
{R}un                | Run program   <AltR>
{P}roject            | {ProjOptions} [Project Options] <AltP>

could be changed to:

{E}dit               | Editor        <AltE>
{C}ompilation
  {C}ompile          | Compiler      <AltC>
  {L}ink             | Linker        <AltL>
  {M}ake             | Make          <AltM>
  {R}un              | Run program   <AltR>
{P}roject            | {ProjOptions} [Project Options] <AltP>

This creates a new submenu under the command Compilation.
The indentation of the menu text (i.e. number of leading spaces)
determines the start and end of each menu. In the above example,
this means that the extra spaces added in front of {C}ompile
cause a new submenu to be started. This submenu continues until
{P}roject where the indentation returns to its previous level.
Look  at the Project Menu for further examples of "nested"
submenus.


Changing ShortCut Keys
----------------------

At the end of a Menu Definition Line, there also may be a
ShortCut key sequence defined. This sequence activates that
function or submenu. You may change or add to these key
definitions to change the ShortCut keys. For example, to assign
the key F4 to the {O}ptions {R}un {C}ommand-Line function, you
would change the line:

{C} - Command line    | Command Line

to

{C} - Command line    | Command Line <F4>

You can specify multiple keys after the line, if you need more
than one key to activate the same function.

You can also define keys independently of the menus. An example
of this is the zoom window function, which is defined as follows:

!Key  | Zoom Window <F5>

You can change, add to, or delete these key definitions in the
same way as changing the Menu Definition lines.


External DOS Commands
---------------------

As you may have already noticed, there is an Action Name after
the | and before the ShortCut keys in Menu and Key Definition
lines. This name defines the action that is performed when the
menu line is selected, or the ShortCut key is pressed.

In addition to the pre-defined environment actions (which are
listed further on) you can also install a DOS Command String
which will be executed under a DOS shell whenever the Menu Line
is selected.  In this way, you can attach your own programs to
the environment menus and keys. For example, if you required
the DOS command

  delete *.bak

as a menu function, then you might add the line:

Delete {B}AK files  | 'del *.BAK' <AltF3>

to the menu  definition. The DOS command required should be
enclosed by single or double quote characters, and may prompt
for parameters by placing %M or %P within the command string.


The Editor Keys and Menus
-------------------------

The Environment Editor has its own specific keys and menus.
These are separated from the rest of the Menu Definition by
the line:

!Editor

Everything after this line and before the line !MsgText is
only valid when within the Editor. If you want to add or
change Editor keys or menus, the you should edit the lines
after !Editor.


Text Messages
-------------

Text after the !MsgText directive (and in included files)
defines all the text messages used by the environment. These
may be translated to other languages or personalized by adding
your own text. The length of most messages may be changed,
but in general it is best to retain the approximate length of
each message (especially when lengthening messages). Some
messages are used as initialized data and should only be
changed with extreme care (or preferably not at all!) An
example of this is the C reserved words.



TSMAIN.TXT Format
=================

The TopSpeed Configuration file contains lines of text that
may be either Directives, Menu Text or Message text. Blank
lines are not significant, and can therefore be used for clarity.
Directives inform the TSCFG program of, Menu Types, Menu Titles,
Conditional sections and ShortCut Keys. The Menu Text defines
the structure of the menu tree and the associated functions.
The Message Text defines the text used and displayed by the
TopSpeed Environment.


Directives
----------
Directives always begin with a '!'. Following the '!' is the
directive name, together with any parameters required. Directives
can be global to the entire environment, or they can be
restricted to the editor.

The directives, together with some examples, are as follows:


Menu Type
---------
You can have three forms of Menu Type directives:

!PopUp [ MenuTitle ] | KeySequences
or:

!PullDown [ MenuTitle ] | KeySequences

or:

!LinePull | KeySequences

Such directives define the type and title of a top level menu
and any ShortCut keys that should invoke the menu. The menu
title and shortcut keys are optional.

The type of the top menu can be one of the following

Line Pull (default), a Pull Down menu with no frame or title.
Pop Up, which has vertical menu selections.
Pull Down, which has horizontal menu selections.

The menu title is text - enclosed by square brackets ( [ and ] )
and will appear in the top center of the frame enclosing the
menu. You can define one or more KeySequences to invoke the menu.
The KeySequence format later.

Example:

!PullDown [ TopSpeed ] | <F10>

specifies that the menu named "TopSpeed" is to be a pull down
menu, and is to be activated by pressing F10.


Editor Section
--------------

!Editor

Generally, your directives will apply to the entire environment.
Sometimes, however, you may have directives that should apply
only to the editor. For example, you might want to use a
different Help Line for the editor.

To make this possible, the menu definition is split into two
distinct sections. The first section contains general menus
and keys, available from anywhere within the environment. The
second section contains editor menus and keys that are only
available while editing.

To split the two sections, the directive !Editor must be
included in the menu definition. Everything above this directive
is global to the environment, and everything down to the
Message text section is local to the editor.


ShortCut Key Definition
-----------------------

!Key | Action KeySequences

You can use the !Key directive to define ShortCut keys that
invoke commands not found on any menu. This directive assigns
the specified action to one or more key sequences.

The format of actions (which can be a DOS command) is described
below.

Whenever a sequence of keys is pressed, the appropriate action
will be invoked. Keys defined before the !Editor directive will
be active anywhere within the environment, and keys defined
after will be active only while editing. An example of an Editor
Key is the Case Correct Key which is defined as follows:

!Key  |  Ed Case Correct     <ShiftF7>


Comment
-------

!! <comment text>
A line beginning with '!!'  serves as a comment on other
material. The line is ignored by the environment, but will be
useful to you or someone else trying to get an overview of the
file's contents. You can include comment lines anywhere in the
file.

Example:

!! TopSpeed C Version 3.10
!! -----------------------


Conditional Sections
--------------------
Sections of the menu definition may be bracketed by the !if
and !end directives these take the form:

!if conditionname

   conditional section

!end

If the condition has been previously set using the !set
directive (e.g: !set conditionname) then the conditional
section will be read, otherwise it will be ignored by the
TSCFG program. These sections may be nested and cannot
bracket messages in the !MsgText section.

Multiple conditions may be specified - for example

!if c | cpp

will cause the following lines to be included if either of
the conditions have been specified.


Menu Line Definition
--------------------

A menu line defines the menu level, the menu text, the command
character, and the function to be invoked, as well as any
ShortCut keys.

The format of a menu line definition is:

MenuText | Action KeySequences

The menu text specifies what will appear on the screen when the
menu is invoked. The level of the menu is determined by the
number of leading spaces before the menu text.

When a new submenu definition begins, its text is indented
further to the right.  When the submenu definition ends, the
text is indented to the left to the same indentation as the
parent menu.

The Action is the name of the function to be invoked and is
described in the following section, "Menu Actions".

Note that menu lines that invoke submenus should not have an
Action defined. They can have associated ShortCut keys, however.

Within the menu text, you can define a single command character
(which invokes that menu line) by enclosing that character
within braces - for example, {E}. A command character defined
in this way should be unique for that particular menu.

Trailing and leading spaces are ignored within the menu text
(except that leading spaces serve to define the menu level,
as described above). If you need actual spaces at the beginning
or end of the text, you should use the underscore _ character.
This will be translated into actual spaces in the displayed
menu text.

A Menu Line may also contain after the '|' character, Help File
Links (contained within the braces '{' and '}'), Menu title
text (contained between '[' and ']') and, after the action,
option definition text. Option definition text (also contained
within the characters '[' and ']') is read and decoded by the
TopSpeed compilers and environment so should NOT be changed.
You may change the Menu Title Text however which determines the
title displayed at the top and center of the menu window.


Menu Actions
------------
The menu actions are invoked either by a key or by menu
selection. There are two different kinds of actions, Pre-Defined
Actions and External Actions. Pre-Defined Actions invoke an
environment command, while External Actions run an external
program under DOS.


Pre-Defined Actions
-------------------
These actions are specified by name. The first eight non-space
characters in the name are significant. The following lists
specify the pre-defined actions, together with the page number
of the section that describes their function. The first list
shows the global actions and the second list shows the actions
accessible in the editor.



Global Actions
--------------
The Global Actions, which may be invoked throughout the
environment, are as follows:

 LoadFile              (load file into editor)
 LoadF RO              (Load file read-only)
 PickFile              (Pick file from pick list)
 SaveFile              (Save file in current editor)
 SaveAllF              (Save all files)
 ChangeDir             (Change DOS directory)
 Directory             (Display DOS directory)
 DOSShell              (Execute DOS Shell)
 Execute               (Execute single line program)
 Quit                  (Leave environment)
 Editor                (Invoke editor)
 Compiler              (Compile program)
 Make                  (Make project)
 Run program           (Run program)
 ProjNew               (New project name)
 ProjOpt               (Project options)
 ModelOpt              (Memory model options)
 CompOpt               (Compiler options)
 MakeOpt               (Make options)
 Command Line          (Command line for Run program)
 RunOpt                (Run options)
 EdOpt                 (Editor Options)
 Default Filenames     (Define default filenames)
 Default Extensions    (Define default extensions)
 No Of Backups         (No of editor file backups)
 Top Scroll Zone       (Set top scroll zone)
 Bottom Scroll Zone    (Set bottom scroll zone)
 EnvOpt                (Environment option)
 Load Red File         (Load redirection file)
 Red Edit              (Edit redirection file)
 Load Macs             (Load macro file)
 Save Macs             (Save macro file)
 Load Config File      (Load CFG file)
 Save Config File      (Save CFG file)
 Asciitab              (Ascii table)
 Calculator            (Calculator)
 Find Error            (Find run-time error)
 WildSearch            (Search for text)
 Search List           (Search pick-list)
 ScanCodes             (Keyboard codes)
 Print                 (Print file)
 PrintSet              (Print settings)
 Review Screen         (Review DOS screen)
 View File             (View file as data)
 Help                  (Enter help system)
 Info                  (Information window)
 Edit0-Edit9           (Invoke editor windows 0-9)
 Zoom Window           (Zoom window)
 Cycle Windows         (Cycle windows)
 CutKey                (Cut text from screen) (Single key only)
 WinKey                (Enter window control mode) (Single key only)


Editor Actions
--------------
The Editor Actions, which may be invoked throughout the editor
but not elsewhere, are as follows:

Ed Load File         Ed Load F RO        Save File
Ed Write File        Ed Find             Ed Replace
Ed Start Screen      Ed End Screen       Ed Start File
Ed End File          Ed Start Line       Ed End Line
Ed Goto Begin Block  Ed Goto End Block   Ed Prev Position
Ed Del End Line      Ed Restore Line     Ed Goto Line
Save File            Save All Files      Ed Begin Block
Ed End Block         Ed Hide Block       Ed Mark Word
Ed Mark Line         Ed Copy Block       Ed Move Block
Ed Del Block         Ed Read Block       Ed Write Block
Ed Get Block         Ed Print Block      Ed Indent Block
Ed Undo              Ed Quit             Ed Opt
Toggle RO            Ed Tab Width        Ed Word Left
Ed Page Down         Ed Move Right       Ed Move Up
Ed Word Right        Ed Del Forward      Ed Del Backward
Ed Tab               Ed Find Again       Ed Ins Line
Ed Ins Below         Ed Prefix           Ed Page Up
Ed Move Left         Ed Del Word         Ed Upper Case
Ed Scrl Down         Ed Move Down        Ed Del Line
Ed Scrl Up           Ed Next Error       Ed Prev Error
Ed Case Correct      Ed Goto M1          Ed Goto M2
Ed Set M1            Ed Set M2           Paste

Editor Actions can only be used as the action within the
Editor section of the menu definition, while Global Actions
can be used in either section.


External Commands
-----------------
Within the environment menu system it's possible to attach an
external DOS or OS/2 command or program to any key or menu entry.
This can be done by enclosing the command line in either single
or double quotes and using it as an Action in the Menu or Key
definition described above.

For example, suppose you have the following menu lines defined:


     {B}ackup Files   | 'copy *.c a:'
     !Key             | "find 'Version' *.h"  <AltZ>

If you select the {B}ackup Files menu entry, then the DOS
command line:

  copy *.C a:

is executed. Similarly,  when you press  AltZ the command line:

  find 'Version' *.h

is executed.


External Command Parameters
---------------------------
Suppose you need to pass the current Project name to the command
you want to execute. You can do this, by including %M in the
command at the spot in which you want the name. Similarly %L
can be used to insert the current command line set.

To prompt for a string you can put %P (prompt string) in the
command string. The %P will then be expanded to the entered
string.

For example, suppose you define:

     {E}rase          | 'del %P(File to delete: )'
     {D}ebug          | 'debug %M.EXE'


Selecting Erase prompts for

File to delete:

After you type a file name (let's say, FTODEL) and press Enter,
the command line:

  del ftodel

is executed. Similarly selecting Debug will prompt for the
Project name and will then execute the command

  debug mainfile.exe

You can include as many '%P's as you need in the command string.


Key Sequences
-------------
The !Key directives and menu entries can have one or more
KeySequences attached. These key sequences  consist of key names
enclosed by the  characters '<' and '>'.

Examples of key sequences include:

<AltA>               Alt A
<CtrlZ>              Control Z
<CtrlQ D>            Control Q followed by D
<CtrlK M 1>          Control K followed by M then 1
<ShiftF2>            F2 Shifted
<Home End>           Home followed by End


The following keys are valid and represent the names to use:


F1 - F10                     CtrlF1 - CtrlF10
ShiftF1 - ShiftF10           AltF1 - AltF10

Alt0 - Alt9    AltA - AltZ

UpArr          DownArr       LeftArr       RightArr
CtrlUpArr      CtrlDownArr   CtrlLeftArr   CtrlRightArr

PageDown       PageUp        Home          End
CtrlPageDown   CtrlPageUp    CtrlHome      CtrlEnd

Del            Ins           AltEqual      ShiftTab


If ambiguous key sequences are defined in the menu definition
(for example, CtrlK and CtrlK B and CtrlK K), then the menu
system will wait a short interval after the initial sequence
has been typed. If the remainder of a longer sequence is typed,
within this time then the long sequence will be executed.
Otherwise, the shorter sequence will be assumed. This can be
used to create automatic "pop-up" menus in the menu definition.

To remove the automatic Pop-Up facility from  the standard menu
configuration, remove the "short" key  sequences - that is,
remove the lines in TSMAIN.TXT containing the sequences
CtrlQ, CtrlK and CtrlO.


Message Text
------------

The message text section is located at the end of the TSCFG.TXT
file and is introduced by the !MsgText directive. Text
following this directive will be interpreted as text messages.
The !MsgText directive when followed by a filename can also be
used to 'include' an external set of text messages.

e.g:

   !MsgText

starts the message text section.

Text messages have the format: decimal number followed by a
single space followed by the message text. Trailing in the
message text spaces are ignored, but if required can be added
by placing a '@' delimiter character at the desired end of
message. In this case the '@' is deleted.

Text messages must be kept in the correct numerical sequence.
However some message numbers may be omitted. TopSpeed compilers
have their error messages within external files and are
included as described above.

Generally it is easy to determine the message use from either
inspection or trial and error. Some useful messages that may
be configured are listed below:

25 -    Default Backup extension
26 -    Backup extension when no of backups > 1
34 -    Printer device as used by the editor
36 -    Characters used together with alpha-numerics to
        define a 'word'
        (as used by next/prev word, delete word etc)
46 -    Character Prefix prompt (CtrlP)
61 -    Yes or No alternative keys (YN)
73 -    Abort/Retry alternative keys (AR)
81-82 - am pm for date strings
119,127,144,145,149,156,181-183 -
        Help lines displayed at the bottom of the screen.
        Text enclosed in braces is highlighted.
        ~nnn specifies the ASCII character nnn, which can be
        used to insert unprintable characters.
147 -   The names of the keys
174-178,185-186,189-190,195-199:
        Various default filenames and extensions
180 -   Search option characters
188 -   Location of OS/2 error message file
193 -   OS/2 Start session command line
210+n   DOS error message for error n
250-264 Project file text messages
310-315 Command line options description
400-460 TopSpeed Run-time-error messages
500-516 DLL Run-time-error messages
